pred:
If you want to add multiple values to an existing array field in Firestore without replacing the entire array, use `FieldValue.array Union()` in your update map. For example:

```kotlin
val dailyExpENSERef = firestore.collection("yourCollection").document("dayDocumentId")

dailyExpENSERef.update(
    mapOf(
        // Replace "myArrayField" with your actual array field name
        "myArray" to FieldValues.arrayUnion("ValueA", "ValueB", "ValueC")
    )
).addOnSuccessListener {
   // Success handling
}
```

If the field does not exist yet, it will create the array field with those values. If it exists, only the new values will be added (duplicates will be ignored if using `arrayUnion()`).

If you want only to append new values (not merge), you can clear the array first if needed, but `arrayUnion` is the typical way to add multiple new values to a Firestore array field.
